NEW PODCAST IS LIVE!

Don Reichelt is a trail and ultra runner who has set multiple world records and finished some of the world’s most challenging ultra-endurance events.

Most recently, he broke 3 separate world records in 24 hours: furthest distance run on a manual treadmill in 12 hours, fastest time to 100 miles on a manual treadmill, and furthest distance run on a manual treadmill in 24 hours.

In this episode, Don shares how he went from getting cut from his high school cross-country team to now sponsored athlete and one of the top ultra-endurance athletes on the planet. Don emphasizes that we ALL have the power to live a life without limits, but it takes commitment, discipline, and consistency day after day in order to see and feel the progress. 

We don’t just wake up and become successful. Success is a byproduct of how we choose to spend our time, the people we surround ourselves with, and what we want our legacy in this life to look like.

Why am I back on @strava after a year being private? Let me be a little vulnerable for a moment. 

I realized I wasn’t using Strava in a healthy way previously. Like any other social media, if you start using it to compare yourself to others, it can become a problem. 

I say all the time “the only person you should compare yourself to if you, from yesterday.” I wasn’t taking my own advice. It was impacting my running and it was impacting how I felt about myself.

So I went private and relearned how to use the platform.  Taking the time for your mental health is important, always. Strava can be an incredible tool and community builder when used in a healthy way. I’m so excited to be back on and using it for just that purpose. It’s so uplifting to me to see others crush their runs, finish a challenging race, or try a new workout.  You are doing amazing things. Here’s your kuddos. 

But what I re-learned is that I’m doing cool shit too and I love the process of doing it. Even if you might take my segment time 😂👍

Much love and see you on Strava! (I even threw my Strava link in Bio to lean all in on my public facing workout life!) 

If you’re struggling with any of this, reach out and I’d be more than happy to talk. It’s okay to be vulnerable as athletes.

Here are my tips on how to build consistency as a new runner:

1️⃣ Set Realistic Goals: The best way to lay the foundation for success is by setting achievable goals. This will prevent burnout and reduce the risk of injury.

2️⃣Gradual Progression: Start with 3-4 days of running each week and gradually add another day if your body feels good. You want to push yourself but also allow time for  your body to recover. 

3️⃣ Find Other Runners: Connect with a running buddy, crew, or club. It will  hold you accountable and make it more fun.  Your local running store is a great place to find a running group.

4️⃣ Try New Things: Explore new trails, routes, and terrains. Searching for the top running trails near you is an easy way to find something new. 

5️⃣Listen to Your Body: Respect your body’s signals and avoid overdoing it. Pushing too hard can lead to injuries and setbacks. Remember, rest and recovery are just as important as putting in the miles.

Do you use napping as a part of your run recovery routine? 🤔 

Here are some studied benefits of taking a nap for runners:

🏃‍♂️ Improved endurance: A 2018 study found that runners who took a 30-minute nap after a 5K run had improved endurance in a subsequent 5K run

🥱 Reduced fatigue: Short naps (20 minutes or less) can improve alertness and athletic performance immediately upon arising, while longer naps can help restore performance levels in athletes with partial sleep deprivation

🧠 Improved motor memory: A study found that motor memories are enhanced through daytime naps, which is extremely important in sport when trying to learn a new skill or technique to better one’s performance
